  "bib_entries": {
    "84539333": {
      "title": "The effect of dietary protein level, water temperature and growth hormone administration on growth and metabolism in the common carp (Cyprinus carpio)",
      "abstract": "Abstract Two experiments were carried out to study fish growth and several other metabolic parameters under three main effects: dietary protein level (40% vs. 21%); water temperature (26 vs. 17\u00b0C), and intraperitoneal administration of carp growth hormone (cGH) (5 \u03bcg/g body weight/week vs. saline). Whereas both higher protein levels and elevated temperature promoted growth, the effect of cGH administration was highly dependent on protein level, the largest growth-promoting effect being found with low-protein diets. The dependence was particularly significant in the first experiment, in which the amount of feed provided was highest (5% vs. 2% of body weight/day). At the lower water temperature, fish in all treatments showed a significantly elevated hepatosomatic index. Protein level and cGH administration effects were unclear. The protein: fat ratio in the body contents was decreased by the high-protein diet and lower water temperature, whereas cGH had no effect. In contrast, the glycogen: fat ratio depended mainly on temperature\u2014yielding higher ratios at the lower temperature, and not on cGH or protein levels. Carp GH administration decreased AcCoA carboxylase activity in the liver. Water temperature did not change the level of GH or T3 in the plasma. Protein level did not influence GH but increased T3, whereas GH expression in the pituitary gland was downregulated by the administration of cGH and by the low-protein diet."
    },
    "84502044": {
      "title": "Direct influences of temperature on gonadotropin-II release from perifused pituitary fragments of common carp (Cyprinus carpio L.) in vitro",
      "abstract": "Abstract The direct influences of temperature on basal and stimulated gonadotropin-II (GtH-II) release of common carp pituitary fragments in a perifusion system were examined. The pituitaries were taken from sexually recrudescing common carp. The basal GtH-II release of the pituitary fragments was suppressed by low temperature, with a significant decrease in GtH-II release at 10\u00b0C compared with those at 20\u00b0C and 25\u00b0C. The pituitary GtH-II release responses to superactive agonist of salmon gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) [Arg6, Pro9 NEt]-sGnRH (sGnRH-A), administered in both pulsatile and continuous fashions, were also suppressed by low temperature. With 2 min pulsatile administration, generally there were significantly greater responses to pulsatile sGnRH-A at 20\u00b0C and 25\u00b0C compared to 10\u00b0C and 15\u00b0C at the three dosages (1, 10 and 100 nM) tested, although this was not as clear at the low dosage. There were no significant effects of temperature on GtH-II release responses between 20\u00b0C and 25\u00b0C, and 10\u00b0C and 15\u00b0C. With continuous administration of 1 or 10 nM sGnRH-A, the initial GtH-II response peaks at the onset of continuous administration, and GtH-II release rates during each hour of continuous sGnRH-A treatment were always greater at the warmer temperature. Continuous exposure of the pituitary fragments at 10\u00b0C or 20\u00b0C to 10 nM sGnRH-A resulted in an initial peak of GtH-II release followed by desensitization to further sGnRH-A stimulation. This biphasic GtH-II response was not as clear at 1 nM dosage, because a rebound in GtH-II release occurred following the initial desensitization. There was, however, no clear influence of temperature on the GtH-II release pattern in response to continuous sGnRH-A treatment. These results provide evidence for direct influences of temperature on basal GtH-II release and pituitary responsiveness to GnRH in common carp."
    }
  }
